VESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG007365%2F1"><gtr:id>E0D9FDF6-C197-4ACB-A869-66D2FC2E74A5</gtr:id><gtr:title>An investigation of the affective and cognitive profile in children with conduct problems and callous-unemotional traits</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G007365/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Antisocial behaviour creates major costs for society, with antisocial children costing the taxpayer ten times the amount spent on their peers and incarcerated adults many times more. A key risk factor for persistent offending is early-onset of antisocial behaviour coupled with elevated levels of psychopathic (or callous-unemotional) traits. Callous-unemotional traits have been found to be predictive of later severe antisocial behaviour, over and above other known predictive factors. Sensitive assessment of callous-unemotional traits in childhood may allow identification of children who are at particular risk of future antisocial behaviour.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Previous work by the grant holder has investigated callous-unemotional traits in three different ways. Firstly, tasks that assessed emotionality and empathy in children indicated that children with antisocial behaviour and callous-unemotional traits were less likely to report subjective feelings of fear as well as being less concerned about distress in others.
&lt;br />Secondly, results from an fMRI study revealed that when viewing fearful faces, children with conduct problems and callous-unemotional traits activated the brain's emotional centres less than their typically developing peers. Finally, data from a twin study demonstrated that callous-unemotional traits, traits associated with autistic spectrum disorder and emotion attribution skills share some common genetic influences.
&lt;br />
